{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/corneal-superficial-injury/diagnosis/clinical-features/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"5e69aa86-5f9e-5643-a7d8-42aa8a7d460f","slug":"clinical-features","fullItemName":"Clinical features","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 3da9e70c-4e2c-490f-8058-cfe7c1ad63d2 --><h2>What are the clinical features of corneal superficial injury?</h2><!-- end field 3da9e70c-4e2c-490f-8058-cfe7c1ad63d2 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item df005129-064a-4dfc-9bc5-a2b3832551a9 --><!-- begin field fca088f3-bab6-446e-adde-e73c31117176 --><ul><li><strong>Superficial corneal injury is typically unilateral and clinical features include</strong><strong>:</strong><ul><li>Sudden onset of eye pain on blinking — severity of pain can range from mild to severe.</li><li>Discomfort or foreign body sensation which may be described as a ‘gritty’ or ‘scratching’.</li><li>Lacrimation (tearing).</li><li>Photophobia — serious systemic conditions such as meningitis should always be considered in a person presenting with photophobia.</li><li>Decreased or blurred vision due to epithelial disruption and stromal oedema.</li><li>Conjunctival redness.</li><li>Blepharospasm (abnormal contraction of the eyelid).</li></ul></li><li><strong>There is usually a history of a precipitating event such as:</strong><ul><li>An object striking the eye or foreign body entering the eye (for example glass, metal or dust).</li><li>Certain occupations are more at risk of this, for example, those involving grinding or cutting tools.</li><li>Children may not be able to recall or vocalise an event.</li></ul></li><li>Difficult contact lens removal.</li><li>Abrasions are more likely if lenses do not fit properly, are over worn or inadequately cleaned.</li><li>Excessive eye rubbing — minimal trauma can lead to a corneal abrasion.</li><li><strong>If a corneal foreign body is present, signs may include:</strong><ul><li>A visible foreign body on the ocular surface.</li><li>Linear scratches on the cornea.</li><li>Subtarsal foreign bodies typically produce vertical tracks due to repeated scratching with blinking.</li></ul></li><li>Rust rings from a metallic foreign body.</li></ul><!-- end field fca088f3-bab6-446e-adde-e73c31117176 --><!-- end item df005129-064a-4dfc-9bc5-a2b3832551a9 -->","topic":{"id":"2e6b8144-f211-5b68-b186-45133d37a07c","topicId":"2d59b81e-832a-46e3-9d29-6d51c4a5141f","topicName":"Corneal superficial injury","slug":"corneal-superficial-injury","lastRevised":"Last revised in June 2017","chapters":[{"id":"c405f1c0-4e8e-53c9-80f0-8af878326237","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"6a87e9a1-1b9b-58c1-86d8-fe5ee1f34a4e","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"16dcf024-1d0b-50df-8cf0-e74719b13ce8","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"e61d3ac5-d7d6-5460-89d2-4e69efa4c406","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"5ec5fd5c-9db3-51d8-af8e-f6e8438761e4","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"7b3b7417-6d1b-5b24-a4e1-addce6978235","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"73e2859b-b945-53dd-8fee-44777b6eedb1","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"7257ef79-0ee6-5dd1-8f49-6cd9806a9644","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"0b2acd6c-f0f7-56cc-b927-720a91bcac70","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"ba1e3260-ca21-51ca-a0d1-9fdc9b116c31","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"0209b951-b3a9-5c3c-a446-ddcd97c45330","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"820190fd-27f7-5d6b-b17d-c521e4d3bd23","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE Quality standards"}]},{"id":"fc0